{
  "doc_id": "16832",
  "text": "The diagnostic efficacy of saliva can be attributed to the fact that there is an ever continuous and intimate proximity of saliva to oral neoplasms and premalignant lesions. Salivary oxidative alterations can be non-invasively monitored for antioxidants, oxidized DNA and proteins and can be used to identify high risk cases of oral cancer [CITATION_1] . In recent years, increasing amounts of research have been performed on saliva owing to the ease and safety with which it can be collected as compared to serum [CITATION_2] . Future research should aim to establish saliva as a diagnostic fluid for primary screening and monitoring of disease progression in oral cancer cases due to its easy accessibility. Further benefits are that the salivary collection procedure is non-invasive, can be undertaken at low cost and without involvement of skilled personnel [CITATION_3] .",
